searchNodes=[{"doc":"library to store and fetch IP geo-location using Database This module exposes common operations as functions. For more complex operations use Geo.Repo","ref":"Geo.html","title":"Geo","type":"module"},{"doc":"Bulk upsert IP location mapping Function inserts a new row if given IP address is not present in the database. If IP address already present then it updates it with new location data. If there are duplicate entries latest entry will override the previous entry. All invalid rows are skipped Returns ordered list which contains result for each entry. as {:ok, location} if entry is valid OR {:error, changeset} if row is invalid.","ref":"Geo.html#batch_upsert/1","title":"Geo.batch_upsert/1","type":"function"},{"doc":"Get geo-location for the given IP address Fetches location data for the given ip_address from database","ref":"Geo.html#get_location/1","title":"Geo.get_location/1","type":"function"},{"doc":"IP Address IP address can be represented by a tuple of integers , which is the type used in Erlang stdlib. OR it can be a string Example: {127, 0, 0, 1} , &quot;127.0.0.1&quot;","ref":"Geo.html#t:ip_address/0","title":"Geo.ip_address/0","type":"type"},{"doc":"Represents coordinate by a pair of latitude and longitude","ref":"Geo.Coordinate.html","title":"Geo.Coordinate","type":"module"},{"doc":"","ref":"Geo.Coordinate.html#t:t/0","title":"Geo.Coordinate.t/0","type":"type"},{"doc":"Ecto schema which represents a location Each location entry is stored as a row in locations table. Schema uses PostgreSQL specific types for few fields. ip_address is stored as INET type and coordinate is stored as Point Specific types are used for these fields instead of more simple types to allow type specific queries. Location is stored with ip_address as primary key. And all other fields are optional","ref":"Geo.Location.html","title":"Geo.Location","type":"module"},{"doc":"Creates changeset for location struct using params params is map of containing changes. Changes are normalised, cast and validated. If there is any error, error will be added to the changeset. See Ecto.Changeset docs for more information. ip_address IPv4 or IPv6 IP address. It can be a string or a tuple (Erlang representation). Multiple types of IP address notations are supported. Such as short notation 127.1 , 127 . All are finally normalised to Erlang representation coordinate can be a tuple of {latitude, longitude} where numbers can be represented as string or float. OR it can be Geo.Coordinate.t() country_code must a string of 2 characters. value is normalised to upper-case","ref":"Geo.Location.html#changeset/2","title":"Geo.Location.changeset/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"Prepare params for raw SQL operation such as insert_all and update_all Params are validated along with auto-generated fields. Returns {:ok, map} when params is valid, {:error, changeset} when params is invalid","ref":"Geo.Location.html#prepare_params/1","title":"Geo.Location.prepare_params/1","type":"function"},{"doc":"Struct which represents location data","ref":"Geo.Location.html#t:t/0","title":"Geo.Location.t/0","type":"type"},{"doc":"Helper module to run migrations in production Make sure database configuration is correct and database is already created. Invoke migrate function to run the migration. Example $ bin/my_app eval &quot;Geo.Release.migrate&quot;","ref":"Geo.Release.html","title":"Geo.Release","type":"module"},{"doc":"Runs all the migration for the configured database","ref":"Geo.Release.html#migrate/0","title":"Geo.Release.migrate/0","type":"function"},{"doc":"Rollback all the migration for the configured database","ref":"Geo.Release.html#rollback/2","title":"Geo.Release.rollback/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"Ecto repository for geo-location PostgreSQL database For &quot;how-to&quot; please refer Ecto.Repo documentation. Example: get all locations from the table Ecto.Query . from ( Geo.Location , order_by : [ desc : :ip_address ] ) |&gt; Geo.Repo . all ( )","ref":"Geo.Repo.html","title":"Geo.Repo","type":"module"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.aggregate/3 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#aggregate/3","title":"Geo.Repo.aggregate/3","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.aggregate/4 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#aggregate/4","title":"Geo.Repo.aggregate/4","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.all/2 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#all/2","title":"Geo.Repo.all/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.checked_out?/0 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#checked_out?/0","title":"Geo.Repo.checked_out?/0","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.checkout/2 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#checkout/2","title":"Geo.Repo.checkout/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#child_spec/1","title":"Geo.Repo.child_spec/1","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.config/0 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#config/0","title":"Geo.Repo.config/0","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.default_options/1 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#default_options/1","title":"Geo.Repo.default_options/1","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.delete!/2 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#delete!/2","title":"Geo.Repo.delete!/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.delete/2 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#delete/2","title":"Geo.Repo.delete/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.delete_all/2 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#delete_all/2","title":"Geo.Repo.delete_all/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"A convenience function for SQL-based repositories that forces all connections in the pool to disconnect within the given interval. See Ecto.Adapters.SQL.disconnect_all/3 for more information.","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#disconnect_all/2","title":"Geo.Repo.disconnect_all/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.exists?/2 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#exists?/2","title":"Geo.Repo.exists?/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"A convenience function for SQL-based repositories that executes an EXPLAIN statement or similar depending on the adapter to obtain statistics for the given query. See Ecto.Adapters.SQL.explain/4 for more information.","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#explain/3","title":"Geo.Repo.explain/3","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.get!/3 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#get!/3","title":"Geo.Repo.get!/3","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.get/3 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#get/3","title":"Geo.Repo.get/3","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.get_by!/3 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#get_by!/3","title":"Geo.Repo.get_by!/3","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.get_by/3 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#get_by/3","title":"Geo.Repo.get_by/3","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.get_dynamic_repo/0 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#get_dynamic_repo/0","title":"Geo.Repo.get_dynamic_repo/0","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.in_transaction?/0 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#in_transaction?/0","title":"Geo.Repo.in_transaction?/0","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.insert!/2 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#insert!/2","title":"Geo.Repo.insert!/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.insert/2 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#insert/2","title":"Geo.Repo.insert/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.insert_all/3 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#insert_all/3","title":"Geo.Repo.insert_all/3","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.insert_or_update!/2 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#insert_or_update!/2","title":"Geo.Repo.insert_or_update!/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.insert_or_update/2 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#insert_or_update/2","title":"Geo.Repo.insert_or_update/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.load/2 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#load/2","title":"Geo.Repo.load/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.one!/2 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#one!/2","title":"Geo.Repo.one!/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.one/2 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#one/2","title":"Geo.Repo.one/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.preload/3 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#preload/3","title":"Geo.Repo.preload/3","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.prepare_query/3 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#prepare_query/3","title":"Geo.Repo.prepare_query/3","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.put_dynamic_repo/1 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#put_dynamic_repo/1","title":"Geo.Repo.put_dynamic_repo/1","type":"function"},{"doc":"A convenience function for SQL-based repositories that executes the given query. See Ecto.Adapters.SQL.query!/4 for more information.","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#query!/3","title":"Geo.Repo.query!/3","type":"function"},{"doc":"A convenience function for SQL-based repositories that executes the given query. See Ecto.Adapters.SQL.query/4 for more information.","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#query/3","title":"Geo.Repo.query/3","type":"function"},{"doc":"A convenience function for SQL-based repositories that executes the given multi-result query. See Ecto.Adapters.SQL.query_many!/4 for more information.","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#query_many!/3","title":"Geo.Repo.query_many!/3","type":"function"},{"doc":"A convenience function for SQL-based repositories that executes the given multi-result query. See Ecto.Adapters.SQL.query_many/4 for more information.","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#query_many/3","title":"Geo.Repo.query_many/3","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.reload!/2 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#reload!/2","title":"Geo.Repo.reload!/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.reload/2 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#reload/2","title":"Geo.Repo.reload/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.rollback/1 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#rollback/1","title":"Geo.Repo.rollback/1","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.start_link/1 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#start_link/1","title":"Geo.Repo.start_link/1","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.stop/1 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#stop/1","title":"Geo.Repo.stop/1","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.stream/2 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#stream/2","title":"Geo.Repo.stream/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"A convenience function for SQL-based repositories that translates the given query to SQL. See Ecto.Adapters.SQL.to_sql/3 for more information.","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#to_sql/2","title":"Geo.Repo.to_sql/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.transaction/2 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#transaction/2","title":"Geo.Repo.transaction/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.update!/2 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#update!/2","title":"Geo.Repo.update!/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.update/2 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#update/2","title":"Geo.Repo.update/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Ecto.Repo.update_all/3 .","ref":"Geo.Repo.html#update_all/3","title":"Geo.Repo.update_all/3","type":"function"},{"doc":"Import from IP location data from CSV file. CSV file must contain first line as header for the column. Columns can appear in any order and optional fields can be omitted. Column names should be ip_address , country_code , country , city , latitude , longitude , mystery_value all additional columns are ignored. Examples $ mix geo.import sample.csv $ mix geo.import sample.csv --verbose Command line options --verbose - log discarded rows","ref":"Mix.Tasks.Geo.Import.html","title":"Mix.Tasks.Geo.Import","type":"task"},{"doc":"Library to store and fetch IP Geo-location An interface between database to store and fetch IP location. Import IP location mapping using a CSV file and fetch location for given IP. Data is stored in a PostgreSQL database. Dependencies PostgreSQL Elixir v1.14 Erlang/OTP v25.x","ref":"readme.html","title":"Geo","type":"extras"},{"doc":"Currently the library is in a private GitHub repository. So to use the library you should use the whitelisted deploy key or use your access-token repo. ssh key pair is present in deploy_keys folder. Don't worry this key is generated and used only to access this repo to generate token, go to https://github.com/settings/tokens and follow the steps def deps do { :geo , git : &quot;git@github.com:akash-akya/geo.git&quot; , tag : &quot;v0.1.0&quot; } # if you are using token # {:geo, git: &quot;https://&lt;TOKEN&gt;:@github.com/akash-akya/geo.git&quot;, tag: &quot;v0.1.0&quot;} end Much simpler alternatively is to clone the git repo and use the file system path def deps do { :geo , path : &quot;path/to/geo&quot; } end These slightly complicated steps won't be there if we publish the library to hex.pm. Using the library Configure database credentials. See for (Ecto.Repo)[ https://hexdocs.pm/ecto/Ecto.Repo.html] documentation for more details about the config config :geo , Geo.Repo , database : &quot;ip_geolocation_dev&quot; , username : &quot;postgres&quot; , password : &quot;postgres&quot; , hostname : &quot;localhost&quot; , Create database and run migration # create database $ mix ecto.create # run migrations $ mix ecto.migrate Create csv file containing the IP Location data data.csv ip_address,country_code,country,city,latitude,longitude,mystery_value 200.106.141.15,SI,Nepal,DuBuquemouth,-84.87503094689836,7.206435933364332,7823011346 Import data from a csv file using mix task # run `mix help geo.import` for more information $ mix geo.import data.csv --verbose Alternatively you can import programmatically using Geo.batch_upsert/1 helper function Access mapping data using Geo.get_location/1 or using Geo.Repo $ iex - S mix # using helper function iex ( ) &gt; { :ok , location } = Geo . get_location ( &quot;200.106.141.15&quot; ) # using Geo.Repo for more complex querying iex ( ) &gt; import Ecto.Query , only : [ from : 2 ] iex ( ) &gt; locations = Ecto.Query . from ( Geo.Location , limit : 10 ) |&gt; Geo.Repo . all ( ) For more detailed information please check the documentation Production Deployment Running Migrations Since mix tasks won't be available in the mix release. A convenience helper module is provided to run the migrations. You can call this function to run the migration from your production environment # SSH to prod server and run $ bin / my_app eval &quot;Geo.Release.migrate&quot; Development To get started you can use docker-compose run PostgreSQL # start database $ docker-compose up # create database $ mix ecto.create # run migrations $ mix ecto.migrate Load sample dummy data $ mix geo.import test/support/import_files/sample.csv Running Tests # start database $ docker-compose up $ mix test --trace","ref":"readme.html#installation","title":"Geo - Installation","type":"extras"}]